    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27a.33-35_0003"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">35</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        3749 North Fremont Street
                        <hi rend="caps">CHICAGO</hi> 13
                        16 May, 1959
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <hi rend="underline">John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt, Poet</hi>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It was good to hear from you and to know that you are happy in your work. And I too wish we were close enough (geographically) to visit and talk; I miss the old associations and the dear old friends, among them yourself. I miss the old excited talk about poetry, as if it were the most important thing in the world, which perhaps it is. The anti-poets still seem to dominate the scene and the critics, with a few exceptions maybe, are contemptible-- I am thinking of Trilling's brutal attack (it amounted to that) on Frost in New York recently.</p>
                
                <p>I am tickled (I think that is the word) to learn that you read my verse to your classes; but grateful too. And very glad that they like it. I assume that you have my volume called <hi rend="underline">Autolyc<del/><add>u</add>s in Limbo</hi>; but am wondering whether you have a slim opus called <hi rend="underline">Brillig</hi>, which is a sort of footnote to <hi rend="underline">Autolycus</hi>. Anyway, I have a handful of <hi rend="underline">Brilligs</hi> around, and on the chance that you haven't seen it, I give myself the plea<del/><add>s</add> of sending you a copy. It's an odd miscellany; b<del/><add>u</add>t I think it contains a few good poems-- and you will forgive the rest! As Richard Le Gallienne once said to me <hi rend="underline">wryly</hi>, over a bottle of sauterns, "One does what one <hi rend="underline">can</hi>!"</p>
                
                <p>Thank you for nominating me to be a chancellor of the Academy of Ametican<sic>American</sic> Poets. I'm afraid I don't know much about it or its acti<del/><add>v</add>ities; and I know I <hi rend="underline">should</hi>.</p>
                
                <p>I've been since Autumn 1942 "book columnist" of the <hi rend="underline">Tribune</hi> here; and that too is a happy experience and a <add>"</add>job<add>"</add>.</p>

                <p>Do write any time you feel like it, or when you have the time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With old affection</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Vincent Starrett</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p>I think the Muse has deserted me.</p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
            
            
